extended_tweet.full_text:
Udemy & Teachable provide infrastructure & distribution for professors (like Substack re: journalists), but to really compete with universities you also need to provide a network & credential.

On Deck does that for founders now, thinking about how we can do that for more skills. https://t.co/9BBOwULKy5

Substack enables writers like Bari Weiss & Andrew Sullivan to leave their jobs and potentially recreate their salary within weeks, and make much more $ over time like Matt Taibbi.

There's an opportunity to do the same for professors. We just need to build the infrastructure. https://t.co/eiZ7TUuGGB

extended_tweet.full_text:
Rob Henderson's theory of "Luxury Beliefs".

People buy luxury goods in order to showcase how rich they are.

It's precisely b/c they're useless that it brings high status, b/c only wealthy can afford them.

The message is: "I'm so rich I can afford to waste money on this."

Society grants ~equivalent status to builders & ppl who criticize society in novel ways.

Why would ppl propose solutions when it's much easier to harp on problems?

To the extent it informs problem solving, it's helpful. 

If not, it's just luxury beliefs:https://t.co/lfr06AUYsY
